      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "AbortOnConnectFail",
      "pos": [
        6614,
        6632
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When set to true, the connection will not reconnect after a network failure.",
      "pos": [
        6633,
        6709
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Set to false and let StackExchange.Redis reconnect automatically.",
      "pos": [
        6710,
        6775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ConnectRetry",
      "pos": [
        6776,
        6788
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The number of times to repeat connection attempts during initial connect.",
      "pos": [
        6789,
        6862
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ConnectTimeout",
      "pos": [
        6865,
        6879
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Timeout in ms for connect operations.",
      "pos": [
        6880,
        6917
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In most cases the default values of the client are sufficient.",
      "pos": [
        6920,
        6982
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can fine tune the options based on your workload.",
      "pos": [
        6983,
        7036
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Retries",
      "pos": [
        7042,
        7049
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For ConnectRetry and ConnectTimeout the general guidance is to fail fast and retry again.",
      "pos": [
        7058,
        7147
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is based on your workload and how much time on average it takes for your client to issue a Redis command and receive a response.",
      "pos": [
        7148,
        7281
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let StackExchange.Redis automatically reconnect instead of checking connection status and reconnecting yourself.",
      "pos": [
        7290,
        7402
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Avoid using the ConnectionMultiplexer.IsConnected property<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7403,
        7466
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Snowballing - sometimes you may run into an issue where you are retrying and this snowballs and never recovers.",
      "pos": [
        7475,
        7586
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case you should consider using an exponential backoff retry algorithm as described in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Retry general guidance<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/mspnp/azure-guidance/blob/master/Retry-General.md)</ept> published by the Microsoft Patterns &amp; Practices group.",
      "pos": [
        7587,
        7830
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Timeout values",
      "pos": [
        7835,
        7849
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider your workload and set the values accordingly.",
      "pos": [
        7858,
        7912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are storing large values, set the timeout to a higher value.",
      "pos": [
        7913,
        7980
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Set ABortOnConnectFail to false and let StackExchange.Redis reconnect for you.",
      "pos": [
        7993,
        8071
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use a single ConnectionMultiplexer instance for the application.",
      "pos": [
        8076,
        8140
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use a LazyConnection to create a single instance that is returned by a Connection property, as shown in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Connect to the cache using the ConnectionMultiplexer class<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn690521.aspx#Connect)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8141,
        8378
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8383,
        8490
      ],
      "content": "Set the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ConnectionMultiplexer.ClientName`</ph> property to an app instance unique name for diagnostic purposes."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8495,
        8563
      ],
      "content": "Use multiple <ph id=\"ph1\">`ConnectionMultiplexer`</ph> instances for custom workloads."
    },
    {
      "content": "You can follow this model if you have varying load in your application.",
      "pos": [
        8572,
        8643
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example:",
      "pos": [
        8644,
        8656
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can have one multiplexer for dealing with large keys.",
      "pos": [
        8669,
        8726
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can have one multiplexer for dealing with small keys.",
      "pos": [
        8740,
        8797
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can set different values for connection timeouts and retry logic for each ConnectionMultiplexer that you use.",
      "pos": [
        8811,
        8924
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8937,
        9012
      ],
      "content": "Set the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ClientName`</ph> property on each multiplexer to help with diagnostics."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        9026,
        9097
      ],
      "content": "This will lead to more streamlined latency per <ph id=\"ph1\">`ConnectionMultiplexer`</ph>."
    },
    {
      "content": "What are some of the considerations when using common Redis commands?",
      "pos": [
        9138,
        9207
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should not run certain Redis commands which take a long time to complete without understanding the impact of these commands.",
      "pos": [
        9213,
        9341
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, do not run the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>KEYS<ept id=\"p1\">](http://redis.io/commands/keys)</ept> command in production as it could take a long time to return depending on the number of keys.",
      "pos": [
        9350,
        9509
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Redis is a single-threaded server and it processes commands one at a time.",
      "pos": [
        9510,
        9584
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have other commands issued after KEYS, they will not be processed until Redis processes the KEYS command.",
      "pos": [
        9585,
        9697
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Key sizes - should I use small key/values or large key/values?",
      "pos": [
        9702,
        9764
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In general it depends on the scenario.",
      "pos": [
        9765,
        9803
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your scenario requires larger keys then you can adjust the ConnectionTimeout and retry values and adjust your retry logic.",
      "pos": [
        9804,
        9929
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "From a Redis server perspective, smaller values are observed to have better performance.",
      "pos": [
        9930,
        10018
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This does not mean that you can't store larger values in Redis; you must be aware of the following considerations.",
      "pos": [
        10027,
        10141
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Latencies will be higher.",
      "pos": [
        10142,
        10167
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have one set of data that is larger and one that is smaller, you can use multiple ConnectionMultiplexer instances, each configured with a different set of timeout and retry values, as described in the previous <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>What do the StackExchange.Redis configuration options do<ept id=\"p1\">](#cache-configuration)</ept> section.",
      "pos": [
        10168,
        10474
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When should I enable the non-SSL port for connecting to Redis?",
      "pos": [
        10505,
        10567
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Redis server does not support SSL out of the box, but Azure Redis Cache does.",
      "pos": [
        10569,
        10646
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are connecting to Azure Redis Cache and your client supports SSL, like StackExchange.Redis, then you should use SSL.",
      "pos": [
        10647,
        10770
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that the non-SSL port is disabled by default for new Azure Redis Cache instances.",
      "pos": [
        10772,
        10858
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your client does not support SSL, then you must enable the non-SSL port by following the directions in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Access ports<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn793612.aspx#AccessPorts)</ept> section of the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Configure a cache in Azure Redis Cache<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn793612.aspx)</ept> article.",
      "pos": [
        10859,
        11172
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11174,
